    <segment id="1" parent="20" relname="span">
A system with various ways of carrying out the same task (flexibility) will provide various methods to choose from.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="19" relname="span"> Whatever method is easier or quicker to the user will speed up the task (efficiency).</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="17" relname="span"> A good example is the family of Windows operating systems.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="16" relname="span"> Microsoft provided at least two methods of opening windows explorer.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="21" relname="span"> One method has never changed from Windows 95 to Windows 2003 (consistency).</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="12" relname="span"> This method is RIGHT CLICK START, EXPLORE.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="6" relname="evaluation"> Neat, simple and fast (efficient).</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="13" relname="span"> The other method is CLICK START, PROGRAMS (for Windows 95,98) ALL PROGRAMS, ACCESSORIES (for Windows XP),</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="8" relname="elaboration"> and its just PROGRAMS for Windows 2000</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="13" relname="evaluation"> %$#@!</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="15" relname="volitional-result"> You have to think hard where they put windows explorer with each new version of Windows.</segment>
